Jury
Explain all of pathfinder second edition but with preferably a regular explanation, and one where you explain it like I'm 5
King Wizzard Eck 3/15/2024 9:36 PM
Icalchemist . . . @Ica Pathfinder 2nd Edition is a high fantasy TTRPG which is a collaborative narrative experience. Gameplay is turn based using dice and character statistics to determine the results of actions with questionable outcomes. Individuals who play the game typically take 1 of 2 roles; The Game Master, traditionally a single person, who runs the game deciding encounters, story beats and guiding the other role through the game while playing as a majority or all NPCs. The other role is Players, which can range from 1 to however many you all feel comfortable playing with. Players typically take control of One Character usually called a Player Character ( PC ), they go through the narrative and leave their mark on it throughout, making choices with the aid of fellow players and the Game Master. Pathfinder consists of 3 phases of play each important to the game. Encounter, Exploration and Downtime. Encounters are typically combat or time sensitive social situations. Exploration phases are usually for over land travel or puzzle solving. Downtime is for when your PCs are not pressed for time, usually between adventures. Encounters; The meat of most high fantasy games are tightly timed combat encounters. Typically when an encounter begins each participant rolls to decide who goes first, than during their turn has THREE actions to use. Almost everything is one or more actions in PF2e such as; Attacking, Moving, Standing Up, Taunting an Enemy, Drawing your Weapon. Through these actions your goal is to neutralize the encounter, either by subduing the enemy or making amends in a tense social encounter. Whenever something is not guaranteed, such as attacking an enemy or you attempting to resist one of their spells you roll a d20, and add a number of modifiers dependent on your statistics. Two numbers are very important when you roll a d20, a 1 which results in a critical failure, and a 20 which results in a critical success. Rolling either of these typically guarantee success or failure of the action. However unlike certain OTHER TTRPGs you have additional options to critically fail or succeed, namely; Rolling -10 or +10 of the target number such as an enemy armour class or a spell difficulty class. Exploration and Downtime: Are concepts that are lesser used, it's best to see if you like the meat of the game that are encounters before delving too deeply in the minutia of these phases.

what is a pictomancer
King Wizzard Eck 3/21/2024 9:13 PM
They infuse magic with image creation, usually paint. It was a popular homebrew class back in 2009ish called a lot of different things like Artist, thankfully FF14 announced a Pictomancer so people are hyped about it again. Abilities depend on what goal the creator had in mind. You can paint monsters and summon things. You can blast enemies with splotches of colours, mixing them so that damage types come about from different combos ( Red = Fire, Yellow = Radiant etc. ) You can paint images on surfaces or the air and make like area denial your core gameplay. You can paint in the air and influence the enemy, red to enrage them, blue to make them sad, etc. There's a lot that has been done and you can do!
